answers.body_markdown:
Short answer: you fail to detect a collision if `tra_x` deviates from 0 even in the slightest. For example collision detection fails for `tra_x = 0.000001`, but in this case there will probably be a visible collision. There are plenty reasons for this happen, look in the comments of the question.

What you need to do is to check if two objects are _close enough_ for collision. You might want to write a function to achieve this

```
bool IsClose(float a, float b, float tolerance) {
    return std::abs(a - b) &lt; tolerance;
}
```

For `tolerance` you can also use `std::numeric_limits&lt;float&gt;::epsilon()`. There is a good example how to use it in the [documentation](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/types/numeric_limits/epsilon).

In a more complex scenario you will probably implement bounding boxes and check if they overlap.

